goals.question: What is the distribution of module dependencies?
goals.visualization: Histogram of the number of dependencies per module
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the overall complexity of the software project and identify any modules with an unusually high or low number of dependencies.

goals.question: Which modules have the most dependencies?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of the top 10 modules with the highest number of dependencies
goals.rationale: This will help us identify the most critical modules in the software project and prioritize testing and maintenance efforts accordingly.

goals.question: What is the average number of dependencies per module?
goals.visualization: Box plot of the distribution of the number of dependencies per module
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the typical level of complexity for modules in the software project and identify any outliers.

goals.question: Are there any modules that are only targets of dependencies and not sources?
goals.visualization: Pie chart of the proportion of modules that are only targets of dependencies
goals.rationale: This will help us identify any modules that are not actively contributing to the software project and may be candidates for removal or refactoring.

goals.question: What is the correlation between the number of dependencies and the size of a module?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of the number of dependencies vs. the size of each module
goals.rationale: This will help us understand the relationship between module complexity and the number of dependencies, which can inform decisions about software architecture and design.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    # Count the number of dependencies per module
    dependency_counts = data['source'].value_counts()
    
    # Plot the histogram
    plt.hist(dependency_counts, bins='auto', edgecolor='black')
    
    # Rotate x-axis labels if necessary
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.title("What is the distribution of module dependencies?", wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
```

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    # Count the number of dependencies per module
    dependencies_count = data['source'].value_counts().values
    
    # Create a box plot of the distribution of the number of dependencies per module
    plt.boxplot(dependencies_count)
    
    # Calculate the average number of dependencies per module
    avg_dependencies = np.mean(dependencies_count)
    
    # Add a horizontal line to the chart with a legend containing the average value
    plt.axhline(avg_dependencies, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Average: {avg_dependencies:.2f}')
    plt.legend()
    
    # Set chart title
    plt.title('What is the average number of dependencies per module?')
    
    # Rotate the x axis label and set a max of 20 ticks on x axis if necessary
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
```

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    source_modules = set(data['source'])
    target_modules = set(data['target'])
    only_targets = target_modules - source_modules
    
    num_only_targets = len(only_targets)
    num_total_modules = len(source_modules.union(target_modules))
    
    proportions = [num_only_targets, num_total_modules - num_only_targets]
    labels = ['Only targets', 'Others']
    
    plt.pie(proportions, labels=labels, autopct='%1.1f%%')
    plt.title('Are there any modules that are only targets of dependencies and not sources?', wrap=True)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    module_sizes = data.groupby('source').size()
    num_dependencies = data.groupby('source')['target'].nunique()

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.scatter(module_sizes, num_dependencies)
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.xlabel('Module Size')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Dependencies')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between the number of dependencies and the size of a module?', wrap=True)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
